This app produces better quality scans than CamScanner, another good app for the same purpose. The focus is good, automatic cropping works well, and it eliminates shadows on the document effectively. But for sensitive documents it lacks CamScanner's ability to encrypt PDFs with a password before sharing. If it had that feature I would give it 5 stars.

The processed images quality is way better than that of CamScanner but the processing speed is slower compared to CamScanner. Would be great if it was faster. But I understand that this may be a trade-off thing. The better the processed image, the longer it will take to process. Camscanner doesnt take into account of the light contrast difference thoughout the image when processing whereas this scanner does.   Also it would be great if there was a batch mode when adding files to the folder as well.

Nice app. I use it to snap scans and upload them to the cloud often.  I give it 3 stars because. There is a bug in the uploading. I upload as a PDF, and when I upload the scan I just snapped, I name the file, and it says it uploaded it. However, when I look at the home screen it doesn't show the file was uploaded in my notifications. The file is also missing from the destination. This bit me and I was missing a number of files I thought I uploaded. It works sometimes, so I wonder if there is an issue with it being on 4G vs WiFi.   There is a workaround - When I do the first upload and it says "uploaded" but really failed, I just try the upload again and it works the 2nd time always. I'm not sure why the first upload fails even though it reports success, but it is very annoying to do this twice. The 2nd time you see the notification screen confirmation which is what I check.  I upload often to the same few places. Having a nice auto-upload feature where I could prefix a name and have the date appended would be awesome and save time.

I use 2 apps, camscanner (and camcard) and MDScan.  I started with camscanner first because I really like their camcard app.  but after fiddling around a lot to get acceptable results, I started testing other apps.  MDScan produced better results on 'auto' than I could get after minutes of tweaking in camscanner. including retaking pictures, changing light source, etc.  if I'd started with MDScan, I would've been done so much sooner.  having used this only very briefly (as that is all that was required) I get the feeling it might have some quirks. (the 'click' sound only worked on the first photo, not the second, third, etc - of a multi-capture) overall, any quirk I encountered was a slight oddity, nothing that affected the pdf produced.  I think this might be document focused, and I have camscanner for whiteboards, etc..  but next time I'm scanning a doc to pdf, MDScan will be the first thing I try.  currently, I'd classify this as the volvo of an app. "it's boxy, but it's good" meanign it's not as pretty or smooth as some others, but it's simple and works VERY well.  so... that's my experience. :-P

After reading some of the comments about low resolution, bad images, bad formatting, etc... I was a little hesitant to pull the trigger.  During the sale, I decided to give it a go.  Taking a photo is very quick, the auto-cropping works well, and the post processing GREATLY improves the image quality.  I have used this to scan and archive notes, exams, etc for class.  Both the black/white and color options work great (color is useful for an exam graded in red ink).  I am really very impressed, as most of the function is completely automated, it creates nice compressed PDF documents, and is very fast and accurate overall.  Anyone who rated this poorly, or felt the camera/formatting wasn't on par with other apps is probably using a device with hardware flaws in it, as this app is exceptional!

Nexus 7 You have to take a photo on the camera as the program does not recognise the front camera. Once taken open the app, import the photo, and then crop and save as pdf etc. Slightly longer process but gives a viable way of scanning for a nexus 7. Will be good  if app can directly use the nexus 7 camera.

I thank you, STOIK! I thank you from the deepest corners of my heart. For giving me a scanning app that I am actually going to use. I have tested MDScan on almost everything: brochures, magazine covers, flyers, visiting cards, cash receipts and almost every other thing that I could find on my desk, including some of my badly scribbled notes. And MDScan invariably dishes out a perfectly legible scan. The many enhancement options also pretty useful in their respective contexts. The only quibble for me is with the setting of border for my scans: app lacks correcting the perspective by either skewing or distort; and batch scanning needs some work. But despite that, MDScan easily blows its competition (except Handy Scanner) right off the water.
